#1¶

a.¶

Face detection and matching

Goal: the main goal is to learning and verify personal identity by using biometrics to map facial features from images

Dataset: the dataset is a set consisting of face images match or not match

Category: this is supervised learning problem since we work on matching or not matching

Measure Performance: Some measures are more indicated for a verification system (i.e. Equal Error Rate), while some other are usually adopted for recognition systems (i.e. Recognition Rate). Moreover, you have also to take into account between the closed set and the open set context. In the first case, all the identities you are submitting to the system are enrolled into the system, while in the second case there could be persons who are not enrolled

b.¶

Credit card fraud

Goal: the goal is determining the fraud on credit card

Dataset: the dataset consisting of credit cards that fraud or not fraud labels

Category: supervised (fraud or not fraud)

Measure Performance: predict class labels in the test dataset and count the number of correct predictions then improve the accuracy

c.¶

Smart Assistant

Goal: the goal is analyst the languages and voices

Dataset: data set commands and voices

Category: unsupervised learning

Measure Performance: compare commands and analyze to the voice from the users.

#2¶

Customer purchasing behavior=> Because we are grouping customer by their purchase and we do not know the behaviors of each customer and labels for behaviors.

Medical imaging=>for distinguishing between different kinds of tissues and genes

#10 Write a conclusion (at most 18 sentences!) summarizing the most important findings of the assignment—what did we learn about the dataset? In particular, address the findings obtained related to predicting the class attribute.¶

In processing the dataset, it is obviously more approachable to use histogram and 2d scatter plot to computing statistics than 3d scatter plot or box plots. Also, the star plot can be utilized to comparing impacts of attributes in limited conditions (two classes), but it is not useful to interpret other statistics. There are almost no relationship or very weak relationship amongs attributes with each other. Besides, from the visualization, it is proved that class 0 is more reliable to predict because of the highness in density and the center spread comparing to class 1. It states a truth that predicting diabetes is more complicated than predicting non-diabetes. From the linear model, the impacts to Outcome from strongest to lowest are Glucose, BMI, Pregnancies, DiabetesPedigreeFunction, Age, BloodPressure, Insulin, and lastly SkinThickness. The linear model and decision tree are about similar in ranking attributes from most important to least important to the Outcome of the dataset. They both result in the strong influence of Glucose, BMI, Age, and DiabetesPedigreeFunction in their results. Also, the two models indicate the positive significance of Glucose and BMI in predicting the possibility of diabetes in patients. Moreover, from computing the models, even though Skinthickness and Insulin are very little in impact to the outcome, there are strong relationships between SkinThickness and BMI, or Insulin and Glucose. This indicates that SkinThickness or Insulin each cannot affect the outcome individually, but if they are pairing with other attributes, they may indirectly influence the outcome by causing impact on attributes that have strong relationships to the outcome.
